{#- SOFTWARE — prose. -#}
<section class="sec reveal hub-rt--alt" id="ppr-software" style="background:var(--color-paper-warm);border-top:1px solid var(--border-subtle);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-subtle);">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="idx"><span class="idx__n">§</span><span class="idx__t">Service fee vs. software</span><span class="idx__rule"></span></div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:14px;">The software subscription is separate.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>There are two distinct costs in running payroll, and it matters to keep them apart. The first is the <strong>payroll software</strong> &mdash; the platform that actually calculates paychecks, moves the money, and submits the tax filings. That is a subscription billed directly by the provider: <code>QuickBooks Payroll</code>, <code>Gusto</code>, or whatever product fits your business. TechBrot does not resell it and does not quote its price &mdash; for that, refer to the provider, because their plans and per-employee pricing change and are theirs to state.</p>
      <p>The second cost is the <strong>management and processing service</strong> &mdash; running the pay cycle correctly, overseeing the payroll-tax calendar, onboarding new hires, handling year-end, and keeping payroll reconciled to your books. That is what TechBrot&rsquo;s <strong>$150&ndash;$800+/month</strong> fixed fee covers. You pay the software provider for the platform and TechBrot for running it well.</p>
      <p>TechBrot is <strong>provider-neutral</strong>. We hold an active Intuit Payroll certification and operate QuickBooks Payroll often, but we recommend the product that genuinely fits your headcount, states, and benefits &mdash; not the one that pays us, because none of them do. The recommendation comes out of the discovery call, with the trade-offs explained in plain terms.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

{#- TAX-LANE — prose. -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="ppr-tax-lane">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="idx"><span class="idx__n">§</span><span class="idx__t">Where payroll tax stops</span><span class="idx__rule"></span></div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:14px;">Payroll taxes, and where the lane ends.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Payroll management includes the <strong>payroll-tax work the software performs</strong>: TechBrot sets up and oversees the federal, state, and local payroll-tax deposits and filings &mdash; the 941s, state withholding and unemployment accounts, new-state registrations, and the year-end W-2 and 1099-NEC filings &mdash; all run through your payroll product on its calendar. That is squarely inside the engagement.</p>
      <p>What is <strong>not</strong> in scope is your <em>income-tax</em> return and any representation before the IRS. Filing the business or owner income-tax return, tax-strategy planning, and responding to the IRS on your behalf stay with your CPA or EA. TechBrot keeps payroll accurate and the books CPA-ready so that handoff is clean &mdash; but the income-tax lane belongs to your tax preparer, and we say so plainly rather than blur it. Recurring engagements include a year-end CPA handoff at no extra cost.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

{#- EXAMPLE — prose. -#}
<section class="sec reveal hub-rt--alt" id="ppr-example" style="background:var(--color-paper-warm);border-top:1px solid var(--border-subtle);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-subtle);">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="idx"><span class="idx__n">§</span><span class="idx__t">Representative examples</span><span class="idx__rule"></span></div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:14px;">How the drivers stack up.</h2>
    <p class="lede" style="margin:0 0 22px;max-width:70ch;">Illustrative shapes only &mdash; not quotes. Every fixed fee is set in writing after a free discovery call.</p>
    <div class="prose">
      <p><strong>Lower in the range &mdash; representative example:</strong> a handful of salaried employees, one state, monthly or semi-monthly pay, no contractors, simple deductions. Fewer runs and a single tax jurisdiction keep the recurring work light, so a payroll like this sits toward the lower end of the $150&ndash;$800+/month range.</p>
      <p><strong>Higher in the range &mdash; representative example:</strong> a larger team paid weekly, employees in several states, a meaningful contractor roster needing year-end 1099-NECs, plus benefit deductions and a garnishment or two. More runs, more jurisdictions, and heavier year-end volume mean more of the cycle to own &mdash; so a payroll like this sits toward the upper end. Your own shape is matched to a fixed number on the discovery call.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

